### EXAMPLE 4: ACCESS_CONTROL VULNERABILITY

**Vulnerable Code:**
```solidity
pragma solidity ^0.4.18;


contract TransferReg
{
    address public Owner = msg.sender;
    address public DataBase;
    uint256 public Limit;

    function Set(address dataBase, uint256 limit)
    {
        require(msg.sender == Owner);
        Limit = limit;
        DataBase = dataBase;
    }

    function()payable{}

    function transfer(address adr)
    payable
    {
        if(msg.value>Limit)
        {        
            if(DataBase.delegatecall(bytes4(sha3("AddToDB(address)")),msg.sender))
            adr.transfer(this.balance);
        }
    }

}

contract Lib
{
    address owner = msg.sender;

    bytes lastUknownMessage;

    mapping (address => uint256) Db;

    function() public payable 
    {
        lastUknownMessage = msg.data;
    }

    function AddToDB(address adr)
    public
    payable
    {
        Db[adr]++;
    }

    function GetAddrCallQty(address adr)
    public 
    returns(uint)
    {
        require(owner==msg.sender);
        return Db[adr];
    }

    function GetLastMsg()
    public 
    returns(bytes)
    {
        require(owner==msg.sender);
        return lastUknownMessage;
    }


}
```

**Security Analysis:**
This code contains a access_control vulnerability.

Here’s a concise, refined explanation of the flaw and the attack:

1. Vulnerable code  
   • The withdrawal function is declared as  
     function transfer(address adr) payable { … adr.transfer(this.balance); }  
   • There is no `require(msg.sender == owner)` (and no `onlyOwner` modifier) guarding it.  
   • All it does is check a small condition (via a delegatecall) before sending the entire contract balance to whatever address you pass in.

2. How an attacker exploits it  
   a. Read the on-chain `Limit` value (e.g. 1 ETH).  
   b. Call transfer(attackerAddress) and send slightly more than the limit (e.g. 1.1 ETH).  
   c. Inside `transfer()`:  
      – It sees `msg.value > Limit` → passes.  
      – It does a `delegatecall` to `DataBase.AddToDB(msg.sender)`. Since that library function never reverts, the call returns true.  
      – Because the delegatecall succeeded, the next line executes:  
            adr.transfer(this.balance);  
        which drains the entire contract balance into the attacker’s address in one shot.

3. Why this is possible  
   – **No access control** on `transfer()`. Anyone can invoke it.  
   – The only gate is `msg.value > Limit`, a trivial on-chain check.  
   – The library call always returns success, so there’s never a fallback or revert.  
   – As soon as the condition is met, the full balance is forwarded.

Take-away  
Always put an explicit owner check (e.g. `require(msg.sender == owner)`) on any function that moves funds out of your contract. Missing that check means literally anyone who satisfies your simple “limit” condition can drain everything.


**Classification**: This code contains a **access_control** vulnerability.

